subsection.theorem:
Matrix representation of a linear transformation


    Let T: \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^m be a linear transformation. Then, there exists a unique matrix A such that,


    T(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x} \qquad \text{for all $\vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n$}

Further, A is precisely the m \times n matrix whose jth column is given by T(\vec{e}_j), where \vec{e}_j is the jth column of the n \times n identity matrix. In other words,

    A = \begin{bmatrix} T(\vec{e}_1) \amp \cdots \amp T(\vec{e}_n) \end{bmatrix}

The matrix A is called the standard matrix for the linear transformation T.

subsection.proof:
For \vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n,

    \vec{x} = x_1 \vec{e}_1 + \dots + x_n \vec{e}_n

Then,

    T(\vec{x}) = T(x_1 \vec{e}_1 + \dots + x_n \vec{e}_n) \amp = x_1 T(\vec{e}_1) + \dots + x_n T(\vec{e}_n)
    \amp = \begin{bmatrix} T(\vec{e}_1) \amp \cdots \amp T(\vec{e}_n) \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix} 
    \amp = A\vec{x}

subsection.example:
Consider the linear system,

    \begin{array}{rrrr}
    x \amp + 5y \amp = \amp 7 \\
    -2x \amp -7y \amp = \amp -5
    \end{array}

In matrix form, this is,

    \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 5 \\ -2 \amp -7 \end{bmatrix}}_{A} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix}

Then, viewing A as a linear transformation (from \mathbb{R}^2 to \mathbb{R}^2), the problem of solving this linear system is equivalent to asking which vector (x,y) does the transformation A map to the vector (7,-5). In this case, solving the system gives the unique solution of (-8,3), which means that the single vector (-8,3) is mapped to (7,-5).

Consider the system,

    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
    x \amp + 3y \amp + 4z \amp = \amp 7 \\
    3x \amp + 9y \amp + 7z \amp = \amp 6
    \end{array}

In matrix form,

    \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 3 \amp 9 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}

Then, the coefficient matrix is a linear transformation from \mathbb{R}^3 to \mathbb{R}^2, and solving the system amounts to finding all vectors in \mathbb{R}^3 which are mapped to (7,6). The augmented matrix is,

    \left[\begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 7 \\ 3 \amp 9 \amp 7 \amp 6 \end{array}\right]

which has RREF,

    \left[\begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp -5 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{array}\right]

Thus, z = 3, y = t can be treated as a free variable, and then x = -5 - 3t. Thus, the solution in parametric form is,

    \begin{cases} x = -5 -3t \\ y = t \\ z = 3 \end{cases} \qquad t \in \mathbb{R}

In vector form, this means that any vector of the form,

    \begin{bmatrix} -5 -3t \\ t \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}

where t \in \mathbb{R}, is a solution of the system. A useful interpretation is to split this vector up into the parts which vary (depending on t) and that which is constant,

    \begin{bmatrix} -5 -3t \\ t \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -5 \\ 0 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
